    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_2378225300" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2378225300" />
    <a title="Helen" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/5809296-helen"><img alt="Helen" src="https://s.gr-assets.com/assets/nophoto/user/f_50x66-6a03a5c12233c941481992b82eea8d23.png" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2378225300?book_show_action=true">Apr 30, 2018</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Helen" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Helen" href="/user/show/5809296-helen">Helen</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/5809296-helen?shelf=fiction">fiction</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/5809296-helen?shelf=period-fiction">period-fiction</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/5809296-helen?shelf=modern-mystery">modern-mystery</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/5809296-helen?shelf=romance">romance</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2378225300" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer12722502722929626847">If the bookshelves categories look confusing it&apos;s because the story runs from 1967 to 1990 and while there is as much love and sex as anyone could want there is also a very ugly murder which isn&apos;t solved until the end.<br/>The novel centres around Emma McAvoy, the illegitimate daughter of Brian McAvoy who founded the rock band Devastation. Emma&apos;s mother had known Brian from youth and hung with him and the band until they began to be successful. Jane was an alcoholic and drug addict who abused her dau</span>
  <span id="freeText12722502722929626847" style="display:none">If the bookshelves categories look confusing it's because the story runs from 1967 to 1990 and while there is as much love and sex as anyone could want there is also a very ugly murder which isn't solved until the end.<br />The novel centres around Emma McAvoy, the illegitimate daughter of Brian McAvoy who founded the rock band Devastation. Emma's mother had known Brian from youth and hung with him and the band until they began to be successful. Jane was an alcoholic and drug addict who abused her daughter because Jane was totally concerned with herself and couldn't abide anything that took away focus from her. When Brian sees Emma (age 3) he cannot leave her with a mother who so frightens the child that Emma hides under the kitchen sink so Brian cuts a deal with the mother.<br />Brian is on the point of marrying Bev, who is already pregnant with Darren, a baby with whom everyone falls in love, including his half sister Emma. Devastation tours and Bev and the children go along, settling down only briefly when the band records a new album. The group are preparing to return to home base near London and decide to have a party the last night in California. It is a real sixties party with crowds of people, many of them friends of friends, and fueled with marijuana, booze and any other "recreational" drugs guests might want. Under those conditions no one could be sure who was in the house at any given time. At the heart of the party Emma wakes to hear Darren crying so she goes down the hall to his room even though the hall lights are off and she is terrified by the monsters in the dark (thanks to her blood mother). She gets to Darren's room where the door is closed and the next thing is her terrified run down the hall followed by her fall down the staircase and Bev's discovery of Darren's lifeless body on the bedroom rug.<br />The bulk of the book follows the development of the band and Emma's growing up.<br />The death of the little boy destroyed Brian and Bev's marriage and left deep scars on Emma who blamed herself for Darren's death because she ran away rather than confronting the two men she saw in the bedroom. She cannot identify the men and the years are full of the pain of her "failure".<br />The characters are real, the situations are believable and it is very easy to become involved with the story. The ending is particularly satisfying and I have done nothing much else this past week but work my way to it.</span>
  <a data-text-id="12722502722929626847" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

